comment:
Gang, although I am not a lawyer, I may be able to shed some light on why AH and many others are able to repeatedly make false statements without repercussions, despite information that disproves the statements. It is a three part wall against prosecuting perjury charges:
1. Despite claims by "me-too", nearly every charge brought to law enforcement is taken seriously and should be. To lay an accusation is a serious act and is listened to, reviewed and considered in context. This is limited by resources and time available to the law enforcement agency and is weighed against the harm the claimed act caused, could cause again and the ramifications of the act being repeated, thus serial murder is investigated more diligently than jaywalking. 
2. In the areas I am familiar with, perjury is a felony and the standard of proof is "beyond a reasonable doubt", making proving the charge significantly more difficult for a crime many see as relatively minor. Top this off with the secondary requirement that perjury must be proved to have been intentional and many District Attorney officers are not willing to risk their reputation by attempting to prosecute perjury. 
3. Many DA's offices are heavily loaded with prosecuting what are seen as much more serious charges with limited resources, do not gain any resources or gain much in recognition from their superiors or the public by winning a perjury case, but lose a great deal by losing that case, making them reticent to even bring the case. 

The biggest loss for our justice system is that lying becomes accepted as a way to gain resources, to browbeat your opponent before and in court and to risk very little by using these tactics. Divorce and family court attorneys have known this for years, commonly suggesting a woman involved in a divorce and custody case include charges of domestic violence, child cruelty and requesting a domestic violence restraining order as the first three shots to open the battle,  charges few have the time or treasure to fight effectively. 
JD is one of the very few people who has the resources not to back down from his Virginia case and potentially subsequent litigation, making it a very rare telling of so many stories and I, for one, thank him for speaking for so many. For him being such a private man, I can only imagine how much he would have preferred to avoid this whole three ring circus...

comment: Amber didn't mirror interests on purpose? Yes, it was unconscious perhaps. But all liars don't lie exactly on purpose. A liar is not thinking:  "let me lie with an intent to be a liar". A liar probably thinks: "I'm so scared of rejection and I know they'll hate me if I say the truth. And so, there is no way I can say the truth or I'll be screwed." They imagine danger or something horrible from people who know the truth,  and so they lie - it's a poor safety mechanism with emotionally healthy people. ( But a lie can save your life in a very abusive and extremely dictatorial environment, which was probably their childhood.) Still, this is not an excuse to think it's ok to lie in every environment. On this thought, I might as well conclude that criminals also don't commit crimes with an intention to be bad criminals - there must be life circumstances that led them to choose crime. Yet it was still their choice. Liars choose to lie, just like murderers choose to murder. And I don't want to pity those people nor leave them unpunished.

DSD,    It’s not just morphing to attract Johnny. Borderlines have identity issues.
They may become very businesslike and corporate, then they will be around someone that is a hippie, and they quit showing up to work, and get stoned all day.
As narcissists do not have a self, borderlines also have identity issues.
Those are two very deep concepts in psychology, a you really have to study psychology to understand them.
I believe with Amber, it was both manipulation to change her style of dress and books and music, but it was also part of the borderline syndrome of having “identity issues.”
Borderlines have a difficulty when it comes to a sense of self.
